	author = {Amgoud, Leila and Ben-Naim, Jonathan},
	year = {2017},
	pages = {25--35},
	annote = {In this paper, the authors introduce 12 axioms that are desirable for weighted bipolar graphs (argumentation graphs with an intrinsic weight, an attack relation and a support relation) semantics.
--{\textgreater} A semantics is a function that takes as input a weighted bipolar graph and returns a weighting on arguments.
1- Anonymity (names do not matter)
2- Bi-variate Independence (does not matter if not linked)
3- Bi-variate directionality (Only depend on its incoming arrows)
4- Bi-variate equivalence (If there is a bijection between the attackers and the supporters, then they have the same final weight.
5- Stability (If an argument has no attackers and supporters, its intrinsic value does not change)
6- Neutrality (Arguments with an intrinsic value of 0 do not count)
7- Bi-variate Monotony (If a has less attackers than b and a has more supporters than b, then a has a better weight than b).
8- Bi-variate reinforcement
9- Resilience (If the intrinsic strength of an argument is between 0 and 1, it cannot go up to 1 or be reduced to 0)
10- Franklin (Attacks and supports of equal strengths eliminate each others)
11- Weakening (If more attackers and they are stronger then its strength is going down)
12- Strengthening (If more supporters and they are stronger then its strength is going up)
---{\textgreater} The 12 axioms are compatible
They study QuAD (first gradual semantics for weighted bipolar AFs) and they show that it violate some of the axioms and it has an irrational behavior.
They then study DF-QuAD --{\textgreater} Still violates some postulate but do not have the previous irrational behavior but suffer from the "big jump" problem.
~
---{\textgreater} They introduce a new semantics that can only be used for acyclic (no cycles composed of attacks and supports) non-maximal (there is no argument with a strength of 1) BAG.
Their Euler-based restricted semantics satisfy the 12 axioms and do not have the "big jump" problem nor the irrational behavior.
~
